data.body:
When I load a DxtCompressed texture with mipmaps, some mipmap levels are black. The high resolution levels are ok, but some low resolution levels do not contain valid data - instead they contain only black (all bytes are 0). I think the problem is that all mipmap levels where the resolution is not a multiple of 4 (which is the DXT block width) are not set correctly. For example, a mipmap level with 120x60 texels is okay. The next mipmap level with 60x30 texels and all following mipmap levels contain only black. 

To quickly reproduce the problem, load any texture with mipmaps where the texture format is DxtCompressed. Draw the image with a sprite batch and use a mipmap level bias (e.g. 0, 1, 2, 3, ..) to view a specific mipmap level:

``` C#
_spriteBatch.Begin(
        SpriteSortMode.Immediate, 
        BlendState.AlphaBlend, 
        new SamplerState { Filter = TextureFilter.Point, MipMapLevelOfDetailBias = _mipMapBias,  }, 
        DepthStencilState.None, 
RasterizerState.CullNone);
_spriteBatch.Draw(_texture, new Vector2(0, 0), Color.White);
_spriteBatch.End();
```

Here is another test: Let's assume that the mipmap level 7 is 1x1. Write some bytes with _texture.SetData(). Then read the bytes with _texture.GetData() and compare them. GetData() will only return zeros.

``` C#
byte[] desiredData = new byte[] { 1, 2, 3, 4, 5, 6, 7, 8, };
byte[] actualData = new byte[desiredData.Length];
_texture.SetData(7, null, desiredData, 0, desiredData.Length);
_texture.GetData(7, null, actualData, 0, actualData.Length);   
bool areEqual = actualData.SequenceEqual(desiredData);
```

The above code works with XNA but does not work in a Windows desktop MonoGame project with DirectX 11 or in a Windows Store App.
The problem occurs with opaque and transparent textures and also with power-of-two textures.
My current workaround is to avoid DXT compression.
